# ── §2. WHAT AXIS-I ADDS — three intrinsic primitives ────────
@C axis-i-primitive-definition :: meta [4!]
  <- atlas-self-arch-axis-i-graph-query-witness
  => "primitive #1 = TRANSITIVE-CLOSURE-OF-DEPENDS-ON.   token <-* (Kleene star on existing <-)"
  => "primitive #2 = TRANSITIVE-CLOSURE-OF-DERIVES.      token ->* (Kleene star on existing ->)"
  => "primitive #3 = SHORTEST-PATH-TO.                   token ~> already exists for 'converges'; new <~> reads 'shortest path between' (bidirectional)"
  => "all three are SUFFIX/INFIX EXTENSIONS of arrow tokens already in atlas.n6 — no new leading char crowds the LL(1) leading-char set per axis-F § ARROW-TYPE-CARDINALITY-LIMIT"
  => "axis-F K=7 → K=10 after axis-I; still under K=10 LL(1) ceiling, BUT crowding warning per axis-F § ARROW-CONVERGENCE-K-CEILING (K=8 is current safe ceiling) — see §4 trade-off"
  => "FOREIGN CITE-AND-MOVE-ON: Kleene 1956 regular-expression closure semantics (the * suffix); Datalog (Ullman 1989) recursive query base; W3C SPARQL 1.1 path operator * — these are NAMING-SOURCE only; the SEMANTICS is atlas.n6's own DAG over <- and ->"
  => "intrinsic justification (NOT foreign): atlas.n6 already uses ~> (converges_to) which is ALREADY a multi-step semantic — meta_fp at line 81 has 6 ~> rows each one a multi-step path. axis-I generalises ~> from the converges-only special case to depends-on/derives families"

# ── §3. THREE CONCRETE ROW EXAMPLES (using existing DSL) ─────
@C axis-i-row-example-1-foundation-closure :: meta [4!]
  <- axis-i-primitive-definition
  => "row example #1 — replace prose-baked closure with primitive"
  => "  CURRENT (line 28, prose-baked):"
  => "    @P n = 6 :: foundation [11*]"
  => "      => \"meta-closure: 15 grade-10 derivations (sigma,phi,tau,sopfr,J2,mu,M3,sigma_n,perfect_number,sigma_decomp,J2_decomp,faction_phi,granville_smooth,...)\""
  => "  PROPOSED (axis-I primitive):"
  => "    @P n = 6 :: foundation [11*]"
  => "      ->* {15 @ [10*]}                 # transitive derives, filter [10*] grade, count 15"
  => "      ->* sigma,phi,tau,sopfr,J2,mu,M3 # explicit one-hop fanout (existing capability)"
  => "  semantics: ->* expands at lint-time to the BFS-reachable set from this node along -> arrows, intersected with the [10*] meta-tag predicate"
  => "  raw 24 invariance: foundation [11*] entry text BELOW the meta-closure prose stays bit-identical; ONLY the prose => row is replaced"

@C axis-i-row-example-2-falsification-trace :: meta [4!]
  <- axis-i-primitive-definition
  => "row example #2 — falsification chain reconstruction"
  => "  PROPOSED:"
  => "    @R clay-iter-50-DEFINITIVE-iter-36-REPRODUCTION :: meta [10]"
  => "      <-* foundation                 # transitive depends-on filtered to :: foundation domain"
  => "      <-* clay-master-cumulative-status @ [10*]   # multi-hop ancestry under [10*] grade only"
  => "  semantics: <-* unfolds the TRANSITIVE depends-on chain back to the named ancestor; lint emits the actual hop-list as a comment for audit"
  => "  use case: clay-iter cascade has 338 entries; today every refinement re-states <- to immediate parent; <-* lets a refinement at depth 12 declare an ancestor at depth 0 without 12 explicit <- rows"
  => "  raw 91 C3: <-* expansion is LINT-TIME, not runtime — concrete hop-list is materialized in audit comment so honesty is preserved"

@C axis-i-row-example-3-equivalence-shortest-path :: meta [4!]
  <- axis-i-primitive-definition
  => "row example #3 — bidirectional shortest path"
  => "  PROPOSED:"
  => "    @C cube-octahedron-duality :: geometry [10]"
  => "      <~> n6-bt-1389-dual-polytopes        # 'shortest bi-path between this node and target'"
  => "      <~> sigma-tau-equivalence-witness    # axis-F § ARROW-PROPOSAL-BIDIR companion (<-> = direct iff; <~> = bi-derivable in K hops)"
  => "  semantics: <~> distinguishes 'directly equivalent' (axis-F <->) from 'mutually reachable through K hops' — the latter today is invisible"
  => "  use case: BT-1389 dual polytopes (axis-F ARROW-PROPOSAL-BIDIR cited line 28534) and meta_fp 6-path convergence (line 81-90) are TWO DIFFERENT TOPOLOGIES that today both wear ~> — <~> separates them"
  => "  composition note: <~> N (where N is integer hop bound) gives bounded shortest path; bare <~> = unbounded, lint warns if path-length > 6 (n=6 self-application)"

# ── §4. ORTHOGONALITY VS PRIOR 6 AXES (D, E, F, G, H, synthesis) ───
@C axis-i-orthogonality-vs-D-through-H :: meta [4]
  <- atlas-self-arch-axis-i-graph-query-witness
  => "VERDICT: COMPOSES with 5 of 6, has ONE MILD INTERFERENCE with axis-F (arrow K-ceiling)"
  => ""
  => "axis-D (@-type evolution, 10 types): ORTHOGONAL — axis-I primitives operate on @C/@R/@F/@P NODES regardless of @-type; transitive closure is type-agnostic by construction. Composes as 'closure-over-typed-subgraph': <-* @ @C means 'transitive depends-on restricted to @C nodes'"
  => ""
  => "axis-E (meta-tag layering, [10*]/[10**]/[10!]): ORTHOGONAL+SYNERGISTIC — axis-I primitives accept meta-tag predicate filters as in row example #1: ->* @ [10*] reads 'transitive derives filtered to grade-10-verified'. axis-E's [10**] confidence-stratification becomes a NATURAL closure filter"
  => ""
  => "axis-F (arrow polymorphism, K=7→8 ceiling): MILD INTERFERENCE — axis-I introduces 3 new tokens (<-*, ->*, <~>). axis-F's ARROW-CONVERGENCE-K-CEILING=8 becomes K=10 after axis-I lands. Mitigation: <-* and ->* are SUFFIX-EXTENSIONS of existing <- and -> (Kleene-star sugar), not new leading chars; <~> is genuinely new but reuses ~ leading char already mapped to converges. Net effect: leading-char set grows from {<,-,~,>,:,=} to {<,-,~,>,:,=} (SAME) — only TRAILING-* and INFIX-~ patterns expand. LL(1) preserved on leading char; second-char branch tightens"
  => ""
  => "axis-G (body-field schema): ORTHOGONAL — axis-G adds named fields inside @C/@R bodies (e.g. measurement_date, freshness_budget). axis-I closure operates on the ARROW-DAG, body-fields are node-internal. They commute: axis-I closure can FILTER on body-field predicates (->* @ {freshness_budget < 90d}) once axis-G lands, which is composition not interference"
  => ""
  => "axis-H (ID-convention .vN + @DATE + @F atlas-id-registry): ORTHOGONAL+ENABLING — axis-H's @F atlas-id-registry block (line 29074-29084) is ITSELF a graph-query target: registry entries become first-class nodes that axis-I closures can walk. Specifically <-* @ @F atlas-id-registry traces every node back to its registered family, which is the natural cross-reference axis-H proposes but cannot express without axis-I"
  => ""
  => "axis-synthesis (recommended sequence D@I → F<-> → F-| → E[10**] → defer): axis-I should be inserted AFTER axis-F BIDIR + NEGATION land, BEFORE axis-G/H, because axis-I depends on axis-F K-budget being known (we need the +3 axis-I tokens to fit under K=10 limit)"

# ── §5. RAW 117 5-CHECK AT REGISTRATION ──────────────────────
