  => "  NOT a single-instance leaf (which would fail genus check); covers transitive-closure + path-query + reachability collectively"
  => ""
  => "GATE 2 / 5 — 2+ cognitive frameworks (cite-and-move-on) ✓ PASS"
  => "  cf1 = Kleene 1956 regular-expression star closure (the * suffix naming source; cite-and-move-on)"
  => "  cf2 = Datalog recursive query (Ullman 1989; the <-* / ->* expansion semantics naming source; cite-and-move-on)"
  => "  cf3 (bonus) = W3C SPARQL 1.1 property-path * operator (the syntactic precedent for arrow-suffix-* on a graph)"
  => "  STRICT: each is named-and-released; the SEMANTICS is atlas.n6's own DAG over its existing <- and -> tokens — no foreign math imported as primary lens"
  => ""
  => "GATE 3 / 5 — 3+ realization channels ✓ PASS"
  => "  ch1 = lint-time expansion (parse-time): tool/atlas_lint.hexa expands <-* / ->* / <~> to materialized hop-list comments during shard absorb"
  => "  ch2 = grep-time query (cli-time): scripts/atlas_query.hexa <slug> ->* — performs BFS over atlas.n6 in-memory; surfaces transitive set on stdout"
  => "  ch3 = audit-ledger-time (post-absorb): tool/atlas_health.hexa records closure-walk depth + branching factor per absorbed shard, falsifier triggers if depth > n=6"
  => "  3 distinct mechanisms (parse / query / audit), not 3 vendors of the same mechanism"
  => ""
  => "GATE 4 / 5 — counter-example ✓ PASS"
  => "  counter-example-1: foundation [11*] atomicity rule (axis-F § INTRINSIC-CONSTRAINT-FOUNDATION-ATOMICITY) — [11*] nodes carry ONLY <-, never -> ; therefore <-* terminates at [11*] but ->* never originates from [11*]. axis-I MUST respect this; lint rule = ->* originating from [11*] node = exit code 4"
  => "  counter-example-2: cycle in <- DAG. atlas.n6 is currently DAG (verified via no SCC ≥ 2 in axis-F audit); axis-I primitives REQUIRE acyclicity. If a future shard introduces cycle, <-* would loop forever — lint precondition: DFS w/g/b cycle-detect (raw 79 reuse), cycle = exit 4"
  => "  counter-example-3: ~> already exists with multi-step prose semantics (line 81 meta_fp 6 ~> rows). <~> bidirectional shortest-path is NOT a generalization of single ~> — they coexist; lint rule = ~> remains for 'this node converges to that' (named single-target), <~> for 'these two nodes are bi-reachable' (symmetric multi-step)"
  => "  3 strict counter-examples bound the primitive's domain"
  => ""
  => "GATE 5 / 5 — novelty falsifier ✓ PASS"
  => "  falsifier-1 = adoption: 30 days post-introduction, < 5 axis-I rows used in new shards → retire (no demand signal)"
  => "  falsifier-2 = correctness: any <-* expansion produces a hop-list with > n*phi/mu = 12 hops → revise (path-length explosion = atlas.n6 not actually a tight DAG)"
  => "  falsifier-3 = redundancy: if every <-* expansion in 30d is a 1-hop equivalent (depth always = 1), the primitive is NOT distinguishing transitive from direct → retire (no transitive content)"
  => "  3 strictly testable disconfirmation criteria"
  => ""
  => "VERDICT: 5-check ALL PASS — axis-I clears raw 117 deterministic gate"

