  => "  G1. atlas.n6 IS a directed graph: 2692 grep-verified arrows over 6760 @C+@R nodes (axis-F § ARROW-COUNT-* counts re-verified for this shard)"
  => "  G2. multi-hop closure IS already authored, just baked into prose: 'meta-closure: 15 grade-10 derivations (sigma,phi,tau,...)' at lines 28/34/43 — these ARE transitive closures, written as => prose strings because no primitive exists"
  => "  G3. ~> already carries multi-step semantics: meta_fp at line 81 has 6 ~> rows each describing a derivation path that is multi-step (e.g. ~> phi(6)/6 = 2/6 = 1/3 unfolds totient → division → simplification)"
  => "  G4. axis-I primitives are SYNTACTIC SUGAR over existing arrows — <-* / ->* expand to BFS materialization, not to a new graph"
  => "  G5. counter-examples 1-3 are ENFORCEABLE via existing lint machinery (raw 79 cycle detect already implemented)"
  => ""
  => "SPECULATIVE (low confidence — flagged as gap):"
  => "  S1. (axis-F K-ceiling tightness) axis-F § ARROW-CONVERGENCE-K-CEILING=8 was a SAFE estimate; pushing to K=10 with axis-I tokens may exceed the leading-char + second-char LL(1) budget — UNVERIFIED on a real parser implementation. Mitigation deferred to lint-tool experiment, NOT claimed proved here"
  => "  S2. (BFS expansion cost) <-* / ->* expand to hop-lists at lint time; for foundation [11*] node n=6 with fanout 15 + downstream depth ~6, materialized hop-list per shard could reach 100s of slugs. Authoring noise is UNTESTED"
  => "  S3. (cycle assumption) atlas.n6 is currently DAG (axis-F audit found no cycle), but axis-F + axis-I together CHANGE the arrow set — adding ARROW-PROPOSAL-NEGATION (-|) and axis-I (<-*, ->*, <~>) could in principle let a future shard author write a cycle by accident; cycle-detect must run on the FULL augmented arrow set, NOT just <- and ->. Untested"
  => "  S4. (semantic drift of ~> vs <~>) my proposed split (~> = single-target convergence, <~> = bidirectional reachability) may CONFLICT with prior author intent on the 25 existing ~> rows. Migration audit not performed in this shard"
  => "  S5. (atlas.signals.n6 read-only scope) axis-I row examples reference only atlas.n6; whether the 4205-row atlas.signals.n6 sub-atlas would benefit similarly is UNAUDITED — the READ-ONLY gate per project policy means no changes proposed there"
  => "  S6. (foreign theory boundary) Kleene * / Datalog / SPARQL are CITE-AND-MOVE-ON only — but the *interpretation* of <-* as 'reflexive-transitive closure' is borrowed semantics. The atlas.n6-intrinsic justification (line 28/34/43 hand-baked closure) is the LOCAL anchor; the foreign citation is a NAMING SOURCE. This boundary is honest but porous — a strict reading might argue any 'closure' notion is foreign-imported. I am declaring the prose-baked closure rows the intrinsic ground; reviewer may reject"
  => "  S7. (no measurement made) ZERO axis-I rows exist in atlas.n6 today; this shard is DESIGN-SPEC. No adoption rate, no false-positive rate, no false-negative rate measured"
  => ""
  => "GAP CLOSED: this shard explicitly distinguishes G1-G5 from S1-S7. The PROPOSAL is registration-gate-clearing only. Actuation requires a follow-up implementation shard with raw 23 + raw 24 + raw 22 sign-off."

